default&#xa0;
default1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRecommendations in the Faulty Goods and Unfair Terms Reports are included in the Draft Consumer Rights Bill 2013. Meanwhile recommendations in the Misleading and Aggressive 
defaultPractices Report are given effect by the Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading (Amendment) Draft Regulations 2013.
default&#xa0;
default1.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHere we summarise our main recommendations and highlight a few areas of concern. Some minor technical drafting issues are considered in the
default Appendix. 
default&#xa0;
default1.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe law concerning consumers’ remedies for faulty goods is unnecessarily complicated and uncertain. Two separate sets of remedies apply where goods fail to conform to contract. The traditional 
defaultUK
default “right to reject” is supplemented by the European remedies set out in the Consumer Sales Directive 1999 (CSD).
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnder the right to reject, a consumer may refuse to pay for the goods or (if they have paid already) claim a full refund. However, the right i
defaults lost once the consumer is deemed to have accepted the goods
default, which may happen “after the lapse of a reasonable time”.
default The case law on what amounts to a 
defaultreasonable time provides 
defaultlittle guidance on how long it lasts.
default In one case a consumer was said to hav
defaulte accepted a new car in less than four weeks;
default in another, the buyer was entitled to reject a car after seven months.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMeanwhile, the CSD introduces four new remedies, organised into two tiers. Consumers must first ask for a repair or replacement. If a tr
defaultader fails to provide these within a reasonable time or without significant inconvenience, the consumer may move to the second tier – which consists of rescission and 
defaulta 
defaultreduction in price. Rescission resembles the right to reject, with one major difference
default: the consumer is not entitled to a full refund. Instead the trader may make some deduction for the use the consumer has had from the product.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOur recommendations were designed to simpl
defaultif
defaulty and clarify the law. In particular, we 
defaultrecommended that the right to reject should last for a “normal period” of 30 days.
default 
defaultBased on research with consumers, we thought that consumers would be able to understand, remember and assert a clear 30 day period. 
default&#xa0;
default1.9
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe accepted that in many cases this woul
defaultd be a reduction in consumer rights: courts would often consider a longer period to be a reasonable time. This reduction was balanced against two further recommendations: 
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe 30 day period would be applied flexibly in some circumstances.
default 
defaultA longer period w
defaultould be appropriate where it was reasonably foreseeable at the time of contract that the consumer would not be able to test the goods within 30 days (for example, where a consumer buys a Christmas present in October, or a lawnmower in November)
default.
default 
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultW
defaulthere th
defaulte period was exceeded, and a consumer was unable to obtain a repair or replacement without unreasonable delay or significant inconvenience, the consumer would be entitled to a full refund without a deduction for use.
default&#xa0;
default1.10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn our research, consumers had been pa
defaultrticularly critical of the deduction for use. 
defaultIt was an inflammatory topic. 
defaultConsumers said that if they had been unfortunate enough to buy a faulty product, and repairs and/or replacements had been unsuccessful, they would feel aggrieved if they were then 
defaultcharged for use of the product. Consumers felt that if the refund were reduced, they should be entitled to compensation for the inconvenience they had suffered (such as taking time off work to wait for repairs). A further problem was that there was no agre
defaulted method for valuing the use a consumer had had from a product, particularly where the product had in
defaulttermittent faults for some time. 
defaultTraders told us 
defaultthat 
defaultin practice 
defaultdeductions for use were seldom applied
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultClause 21(1) of the B
defaultill implements a 30 day right to reject. 
defaultHowever
default:
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthere is no extension for goods likely to be tested 
defaultonly 
defaultafter a period of 30 days (such 
defaultas 
defaultthe Christmas present bought in October, or 
defaultthe
default lawnmower in November)
default.
default 
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultU
defaultnder 
defaultclause
default 24(5), the final right to re
defaultject is subject to a deduction for use. 
defaultClause
defaults
default 24(6) to (8
default)
default set out some limits: where goods do not have a proven second-hand value, no deduction can be made where the right is exercised within six months. 
defaultH
defaultowever, this may do little to limit the
default deductio
defaultns for use
default. With e
defaultB
defaultay, it is possible to show a second-hand market in almost any good (even if second-hand prices are extremely low). 
default&#xa0;
default1.12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe fear that disputes over deductions for use may undermine the simplicity and certainty of the new rights. 
defaultThere is no obvious way to value a consumer’s use of a product, with differences of view on whether one should look at depreciation over time or second-hand values. There is also scope for dispute about how one should account for intermittent faults, time 
defaultspent waiting for repairs, and the effect of a replacement which also proves to be faulty. 
defaultWe would suggest that the Committee examines 
defaultclause
defaults 24(6) to (8)
default 
defaultin depth, to see if any further limits to the deduction for use can be made to reduce the potential
default for disputes in this area.
default&#xa0;
default1.13
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the Appendix we raise drafting concerns about how clause 19 deals with part-exchange contracts.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Law Commission and Scottish Law Commission have long been concerned 
defaultwith
default simplify
defaulting
default the law on unfair contract terms. In 2005 we published a report on this subject,
default 
defaultwhich we updated in 2013. 
default&#xa0;
default1.15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe most controversial area is the exemption for subject matter and price, as set out in 
defaulta
defaultrticle 4(2) of the Unfair Terms Directive (UTD).
default The UT
defaultD states that a fairness assessment may not relate to “the definition of the subject mater of the contract” or to “the adequacy of the price and remuneration… as against the services or goods supplied in exchange”, provided that the term is “in plain intel
defaultligible language”. These words have been copied out in 
defaultr
defaultegulation 6(2) of the Unfair Terms in Consumer Contract Regulations 1999 (UTCCR),
default and have proved particularly difficult to interpret. 
default&#xa0;
default1.16
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe issue has generated complex litigation, culminating in the 
default2009 Supreme Court decision, 
defaultOffice of Fair Trading v Abbey National plc
default.
default The Supreme Court held that charges for unauthorised overdrafts were price terms and thus exempt from a fairness assessment. A large majority of c
defaultonsultees agreed that the law i
defaults no
defaultw unduly uncertain. Consumer groups and enforcement bodies felt that this undermined the effectiveness of the legislation.
default&#xa0;
default1.17
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn a world of price comparison websites, there is increasing pressure on traders to advertise low headline prices, whilst earning the
defaultir profits through other charges. Given this potential undermining of competition, the law should provide effective tools to combat unfair charges buried in small print. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.18
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe current uncertainty has the potential to damage businesses as well as consumers. 
defaultIf a business uses an ancillary price term to subsidise a low headline price, the business is put at risk if the term is later found to be unfair. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.19
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe made 3
default3
default recommendations to simply the law on unfair contract terms. The central refor
defaultm was that the exemptions for price and main subject matter should be reformulated to apply only to terms which are transparent and prominent. 
default&#xa0;
default1.20
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Annex to the UTD contains “an indicative and non-exhaustive list of terms which may be regarded as unfair”. 
defaultThis “grey list” is reproduced word for word in 
defaults
defaultchedule 2 of the UTCCR. We reviewed the grey list and recommended that:
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe grey list should be retained, substantially in its current form, with three additions. These are terms which have the object or 
defaulteffect of:
default(a)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultpermitting the trader to claim disproportionately high sums in compensation or for services which have not been supplied, where the consumer has attempted to cancel the contract; 
default(b)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultgiving the trader discretion to decide the amount of the price af
defaultter the consumer has become bound by the contract; and
default(c)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultgiving the trader discretion to decide the subject matter of the contract after the consumer has become bound by it.
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe legislation should clarify that all terms on the grey list should be reviewable 
defaultfor fairness, irre
defaultspective of whether they also fa
defaultll within the exemption
default 
defaultfor main subject matter and price
default.
default(3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe legislation should clarify that the exceptions to the grey list (in paragraph 2 of 
defaults
defaultchedule 2) may be revi
defaultewed for fairness unless they fa
defaultll wi
defaultthin the exemption for main subject matter and price. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.21
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe are very pleased to see that the Bill implements almost all of our recommendations
default.
default In particular, 
defaultc
defaultlause 67 implements our recommendation that the exclusion for main subje
defaultct matter and price should apply only if the term is transparent and prominent. 
default&#xa0;
default1.22
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMeanwhile 
defaults
defaultchedule 2 includes our recommended additions to the grey list (at paragraphs 5, 12 and 14). The effect of the grey list is also clarified at 
defaultclause
defaults 66(2) and 67(7)
default. We have some minor drafting concerns about the grey list which are set out in 
defaultthe 
defaultAppendix
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.23
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe have only one main concern about the Bill: 
defaultc
defaultlause 71(2) states that if a term of a consumer contract is especially 
defaultonerous or unusual, the trader must ensure that the term is drawn particularly to the consumer’s attention. Clause 71(3) states that it is to be determined, in particular, by reference to the main subject matter of the contract. This does not follow from o
defaultur recommendations.
default&#xa0;
default1.24
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is not clear what consequences arise from a failure to draw a term to the consumer’s attention. We think that the clause could be misunderstood as 
defaultproviding a gloss on the fairness test. If so, this would be a retrograde step. We wer
defaulte persuaded by the strong arguments put to us that the fairness test set out 
defaultin 
defaultthe UTD should be retained in its current form. 
default&#xa0;
default1.25
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultInstead, we recommended that the issue of whether a term i
defaults
default unusual or onerous should be part of the prominence test. In Recomm
defaultendation 7 we said that:
defaultTo be prominent a term must be presented in such a way that the average consumer would be aware of the term. The more unusual or onerous the term, the more prominent it needs to be.
default 
default1.26
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe do not think that prominence should be an all
default or nothing test. Some terms need to be more prominent than others. We think that clause 67(4) could usefully be looked at again. 
default&#xa0;
default1.27
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOur intention was that terms should be “appropriately prominent”, so that an average consumer would be aware of the term. We 
defaultthink that it might be helpful for the legislation to state that in deciding whether a term is appropriately prominent the court should consider several factors, including whether the term is unusual or onerous. Another factor may be whether the prominence
default is in line with guidance prepared by regulators (as set out in Recommendation 10).
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.28
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAt present, misleading and aggressive trade practices are covered by two s
defaultources
default of law
default:
default The Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008 
default(
defaultthe 
default2008 Regulations)
default 
defaultdeal with public enforcement
default, 
defaultwhile private rights are dealt with by a complex mix of common law and statute, under the law of misrepresentation and duress. 
default&#xa0;
default1.29
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOur recommen
defaultdations provide a targeted private right of redress for misleading and aggressive practices under the 2008 Regulations. We had four aims
default:
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulto provide a simpler alternative 
defaultto the law of misrepresentation
default.
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulto provide greater protection to consumers for aggre
defaultssive practice
default. We were given many examples of elderly consumers who were sold expensive mobility aids by aggressive door-to-door sales staff who refused to leave when asked; and lengthy “holiday club” presentations where burly door staff gave the impressi
defaulton that consumers could not leave until they had signed the contract. Consumers do not necessarily have a clear remedy in such circumstances
default.
default(3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulto clarify that the 2008 Regulations apply to unfair payment collection
default. We were told about many misleading and ag
defaultgressive demands for payment, not just following a sale but also for civil compensation following alleged wrongful acts, such as car parking, copyright infringement or shoplifting. We recommended that the 
default2008 
defaultRegulations should clarify that commercial dem
defaultands for payment are included within the definition of commercial practices and should not be misleading or unduly aggressive. We thought that where the money was not owed, consumers should be given a clear and simple right to a refund
default.
default 
default 
default(4)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulto recommend
default reme
defaultdies that could
default be applied easily, without the need for complex evidence
default. 
defaultStakeholders told us that there was a need for certain, standardised remedies, even if these were sometime “rough and ready”. 
default1.30
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe are pleased that the Government has accepted almost 
defaultall of our recommendations. However, in some places the drafting of the
default 2013 Amendment
default Regulations appears complex and may be difficult to understand. We think that there is some scope for simplifying 
defaultthis draft
default, and would be happy to provide further evidence on this issue. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAppendix:default defaultCOnsumer rights bill-defaultDrafting issuesdefault&#xa0;
default1.31
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs currently drafted, clause 19 does not appear to provide a consumer with a refund if they:
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultpaid for a good by part-exchange; and
default 
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultit is not possible to receive back in the original state what the consumer paid.
default&#xa0;
default1.32
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAn example would be where 
defaulta consumer purchases a second-hand car and pays for it with a combination of £6,000 cash and an old car worth £1,000.
default 
defaultThe car proves to be faulty and the consumer rejects it. 
default&#xa0;
default1.33
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnder clause 19(7) the consumer has a right to a refund of the £6,000. Under cla
defaultuse 19(8) they also have the right to receive back the old car. However, if the trader sells or scraps the old car before the consumer exercises the right to reject, then clause 19(12)(b) applies: “the thing transferred cannot be given back in its original
default state”. Clause 19(12) says that in these circumstances “there is no right to a refund”. At first sight it would appear that the consumer is not entitled to a refund of either the original £6,000 payment or £1,000 in lieu of the old car.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.34
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe do not think t
defaulthat this is intended. We think that if a part-exchanged good cannot be returned, the consumer should be refunded money in lieu.
default 
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.35
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe City of London Law Society (CLLS) argues that paragraph 14 of schedule 2(2) should be
default made subject to clause 24 of schedule 2(2).
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.36
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe CLLS state that paragraph 14 is drafted too widely and therefore unintentionally catches price escalation clauses. This causes uncertainty to th
defaultose who supply ongoing services.
default The CLLS suggests that paragraph 14 be amended to state that, in addition to being subject to paragraphs 25 and 26, it i
defaults also subject to paragraph 24 (which excludes variation clauses where the trader gives reasonable notice and 
defaultthe consumer may then
default dis
defaultsolve the contract). 
default&#xa0;
default1.37
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe support the CLLS
default recommendation, and think that paragraph 14 should be
default 
defaultsubject to paragraph 24.
